how to start.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:08.770
TRACY MC CUBBIN: So one of the
things that comes into play

00:01:08.770 --> 00:01:10.990
with it-- it's a little bit
of time management issues.

00:01:10.990 --> 00:01:14.610
It's about blocking off time to
say, OK, I'm going to take

00:01:14.610 --> 00:01:16.400
15 minutes at the start
of every day.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:18.940
Or I'm going to take a half an
hour on Tuesday, and I'm just

00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:20.470
going to deal with the
things on my desk.

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:23.800
And if you can just build that
time in and actually do it,

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:25.580
you're going to stay on top of
it, and you're not going to

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:27.370
get so upside down that
you don't even

00:01:27.370 --> 00:01:28.170
know where to start.

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:29.960
SALLY HORCHOW: So there are so
many things on this desk that

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:31.970
